<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,261,1728]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,473,441,468]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Redescription. Female.</emphasis>
Head, legs, anterior half of the pronotal disc, tegmina and thoracic sternites chocolatebrown (
<figureCitation box="[239,344,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (female) A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468004/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
). Tegmina with a yellow spot on the base and another ovoid spot, near the tip (
<figureCitation box="[1247,1360,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (female) A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468004/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 11C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1373,1424,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1708,1733]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1436,174,1689]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468006/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">12C</figureCitation>
). Thoracic pleura, lateral lobes and distal half of the pronotum bright green; thoracic tergites black; abdomen and hind tarsi cream-whitish. Hind wings dull brown with greenish-yellow venation (coloration data see in some additional specimens; in female 
<typeStatus box="[400,503,585,611]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">lectotype</typeStatus>
they did not keep very well). Head elongate, globose eyes and protruding notoriously towards the sides of the cephalic capsule (
<figureCitation box="[692,803,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (female) A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468004/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 11B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[815,865,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1708,1733]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1436,174,1689]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468006/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">12B</figureCitation>
), fastigium of vertex rounded and not prolongated, vertex medially much lower than the dorsal surface of the eyes; frontal costa short and very narrow scutellum, in side view highly arcuate in the lateral carinae region; dorsal carina of frontal costa moderately pronounced between the eyes (
<figureCitation box="[262,366,729,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (female) A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468004/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
). Pronotum flat, extending beyond the abdomen. prominent and curved spine which covers a great deal of the vertex; median carina continuous, slightly elevated from the anterior margin to the tip; lateral lobes of the pronotum square-shaped, with a rounded lower margin and converging into the lower margin in a triangle. Tegmina short, with a round, apical or subapical, and a more diffuse proximal spot (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1206,837,863]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (female) A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468004/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 11C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1218,1268,837,863]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1708,1733]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1436,174,1689]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468006/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">12C</figureCitation>
). Legs slender, compressed; fore femora indistinctly sulcate above for dorsal edge, with a short external dorso-apical spine; mid femora with a well-developed carinae, and with an internal, dorso-apical spine; ventro-apically; hind femora with two or three lobes along the dorsal edge (
<figureCitation box="[637,719,945,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1415,1440]" captionTargetBox="[174,1414,174,1396]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[174,1414,174,1396]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Characters used in phylogeny. A. Scaria ferruginea Hancock, 1909 (habitus in dorsal view). B. Apex of pronotum in dorsal view of B. flavonotata. C–F. Head and pronotum in lateral view: C. S. ferruginea. D. T. parradae. E. S. laeta. F. S. producta. G and H. Fore and mid legs respectively of S. rafaeli. I. Hind femur of S. producta. J–M. Tegmina: J. S. laeta. K. S. granti sp. nov. L. S. jonasi sp. nov. M. S. ferruginea. Numbers indicate characters and states used in the cladistics analysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3467982" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3467982/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<date box="[692,719,945,971]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">2I</date>
</figureCitation>
). Abdomen cylindrical, with no sternal or tergal modification. Subgenital plate with a broad, shallow emargination, medially subtruncate (
<figureCitation box="[998,1097,981,1007]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (female) A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468004/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 11F</figureCitation>
); dorsal ovipositor valves narrowing distad and apically upturned (
<figureCitation box="[569,669,1017,1043]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1411,294,1892]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (female) A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468004/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,261,1728]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,372,1053,1080]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Male (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[276,355,1054,1080]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">novum</emphasis>
).
</emphasis>
Similar to the female in coloration and structure (
<figureCitation box="[935,1026,1053,1079]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1708,1733]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1436,174,1689]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468006/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 12</figureCitation>
A–D), without any significant variation. Subgenital plate cupuliform, epiproct ovoid, longer than wide, with cylindrical cerci tapering slightly towards the tip (
<figureCitation box="[237,330,1125,1151]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1708,1733]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1436,174,1689]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Scaria producta Hancock, 1907 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in lateral view. F. Terminalia in ventral view. (Photos: Gustavo Tavares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468006/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 12</figureCitation>
E-11F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,261,1728]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1161,1188]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Variation.</emphasis>
According to the examined specimens, the lobes of the dorsal margin of hind femora are more prominent in 
<collectingCountry box="[243,294,1198,1224]" name="Peru" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Peru</collectingCountry>
populations than those of Amazonian 
<collectingCountry box="[725,796,1197,1223]" name="Brazil" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and these lobes tend to be more prominent in females. A male specimen, photographed by Rob Westerduijn, has an anterior spine thicker than usual in stark contrast with the specimens available (three times wider than normal).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,261,1728]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,384,1306,1332]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Measurements:</emphasis>
CFP: 11,93-9,06; HE: 0,65-0,60; VW: 1,4-0,8; PL: 14,6-12,6; PLB: 3-2,6; FF: 2,7-2,3; FL: 2,8-2,6; MFL: 3-2,8; MTL: 3,1-2,9; HL: 7.6-6; HW: 2,4-2,1.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,261,1728]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1377,1404]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[360,473,1377,1403]" name="Colombia" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[486,554,1377,1403]" name="Brazil" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and Peruvian Amazon. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bruner, L." box="[827,987,1377,1404]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="89 - 143" refId="ref30476" refString="Bruner, L. (1910) South American Tetrigidae. Annals of the Carnegie Museum, 7, 89 - 143." type="journal article" year="1910">Bruner (1910)</bibRefCitation>
reports this species for Santarem, Para, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,222,1413,1439]" name="Brazil" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, but unfortunately he failed to specify the number and sex of the specimens; the same author, ten years later (
<bibRefCitation author="Bruner, L." box="[159,312,1449,1475]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="5 - 91" refId="ref30499" refString="Bruner, L. (1920 [1919]) Saltatorial Orthoptera from South America and the Isle of Pines. Annals of the Carnegie Museum, 13, 5 - 91." type="journal article" year="1920">Bruner, 1920</bibRefCitation>
), reports a female (C.M. Acc. No. 6008) from 
<collectingCountry box="[844,929,1449,1475]" name="Bolivia" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, “Rio Japacani”, with dubious ID; the specimen could not be located, so we are not including it for the distribution range. 
<bibRefCitation author="Liebermann, J." box="[1050,1270,1485,1512]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="329 - 344" refId="ref32266" refString="Liebermann, J. (1955) Primeira relacao sistematica dos Acridoideos do Brasil. Memorias do Instituto Oswaldo Cruz, 53 (2 - 4), 329 - 344. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0074 - 02761955000200011" type="journal article" year="1955">Liebermann (1955)</bibRefCitation>
, mentions that the species is distributed in Santarem, citing the original description, which is mistaken. Perhaps Liebermann meant 
<bibRefCitation author="Bruner, L." box="[151,314,1557,1584]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="89 - 143" refId="ref30476" refString="Bruner, L. (1910) South American Tetrigidae. Annals of the Carnegie Museum, 7, 89 - 143." type="journal article" year="1910">Bruner (1910)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,261,1728]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1593,1620]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Comments.</emphasis>
In the original description Hancock reports a male and a female, but apparently the male was lost and was not reported not inventoried in the ANSP type specimen list (
<bibRefCitation author="Otte, D." box="[927,1050,1629,1655]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="26 - 87" refId="ref32832" refString="Otte, D. (1979 [1978]) The primary types of Orthoptera (Saltatoria, Blattodea, Phasmatodea, and Mantodea) at the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 130, 26 - 87." type="journal article" year="1979">Otte, 1979</bibRefCitation>
), so we describe the male here and we designate the only female that could be located as a 
<typeStatus box="[782,885,1665,1691]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">lectotype</typeStatus>
(Art. 74 ICZN). The female 
<typeStatus box="[1214,1317,1665,1691]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">lectotype</typeStatus>
is in good condition, with only the left mid-leg and right tarsus missing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
